sections.english:
At Sāvatthī.

King Pasenadi of Kosala, seated to one side, said this to the Blessed One: "Here, venerable sir, as I was alone in seclusion, this thought arose in my mind: 'Few are those beings in the world who, having obtained abundant wealth and possessions, do not become intoxicated, are not heedless, do not fall into craving for sensual pleasures, and do not act wrongly towards other beings. However, more numerous are those beings in the world who, having obtained abundant wealth and possessions, do become intoxicated, are heedless, fall into craving for sensual pleasures, and act wrongly towards other beings.'"

"It is so, great king, it is so, great king! Few are those beings in the world, great king, who, having obtained abundant wealth and possessions, do not become intoxicated, are not heedless, do not fall into craving for sensual pleasures, and do not act wrongly towards other beings. However, more numerous are those beings in the world who, having obtained abundant wealth and possessions, do become intoxicated, are heedless, fall into craving for sensual pleasures, and act wrongly towards other beings."

Infatuated with sensual pleasures and possessions, greedy and deluded by sensual pleasures;
They do not discern the excessive danger, like deer at a trap that has been laid;
Their future is bitter, and its karmic result is evil.

The Blessed One said to King Pasenadi of Kosala, who was sitting to one side, “Well, great king, where have you come from so early in the day?”

“My grandmother, venerable sir, has passed away. She was aged, grown old, advanced in years, having reached the end of her lifespan, a hundred and twenty years old by birth. My grandmother, venerable sir, was dear to me and delightful. If, venerable sir, I could obtain a wish by means of a precious elephant, that 'May my grandmother not die,' I would give a precious elephant for that wish, that 'May my grandmother not die.' If, venerable sir, I could obtain a wish by means of a precious horse, that 'May my grandmother not die,' I would give a precious horse for that wish, that 'May my grandmother not die.' If, venerable sir, I could obtain a wish by means of the best village, that 'May my grandmother not die,' I would give the best village for that wish, that 'May my grandmother not die.' If, venerable sir, I could obtain a wish by means of a district or region, that 'May my grandmother not die,' I would give a district or region for that wish, that 'May my grandmother not die.'”

“All beings, great king, are subject to death, have death as their ultimate conclusion, and cannot escape death.”

“It is amazing, venerable sir! It is astounding, venerable sir! How well spoken this has been by the Blessed One, venerable sir: 'All beings are subject to death, have death as their ultimate conclusion, and cannot escape death!'”

“So it is, great king, so it is, great king! All beings are subject to death, have death as their ultimate conclusion, and cannot escape death. Just as, great king, whatever kinds of potter's vessels, both raw and fired, all of them are subject to breaking, have breaking as their ultimate conclusion, and cannot escape breaking; just so, great king, all beings are subject to death, have death as their ultimate conclusion, and cannot escape death.”

All beings will die, for life has death as its end;
They will go according to their actions, experiencing the results of wholesome and unwholesome deeds;
Those who perform unwholesome deeds go to the lower realms, while those who perform wholesome deeds go to the happy destinations.
Therefore, one should perform wholesome deeds, an accumulation for the future;
For wholesome deeds are a support for beings in the next world.
